abstract: Ms. Warren seeks to break up companies like Amazon, Google, Apple and Facebook. And she has taken her fight to Silicon Valley.
snippet: Ms. Warren seeks to break up companies like Amazon, Google, Apple and Facebook. And she has taken her fight to Silicon Valley.
lead_paragraph: Senator Elizabeth Warren of Massachusetts believes that the government must break up monopolies and promote competitive markets. That’s why she has taken aim at America’s largest tech companies.

headline_main: Analysis of the First 2020 Democratic Debate

abstract: Democratic presidential candidates raised concerns this week about a government-run shelter for migrant children, where children face lengthy stays.
snippet: Democratic presidential candidates raised concerns this week about a government-run shelter for migrant children, where children face lengthy stays.
lead_paragraph: HOMESTEAD, Fla. — About half of the roughly 2,300 children confined in a privately run Florida facility intended as a temporary shelter for migrant teenagers have been there for more than 20 days and many of them for months, despite legal standards that require children who cross the border to be speedily released or sent to state-licensed shelters that are equipped to offer longer-term care.

headline_main: Opinion | Democratic Debate Commentary and Analysis

abstract: Ms. Cabán’s showing in the Queens district attorney primary revealed that progressive supporters can rally national support and money for a local race.
snippet: Ms. Cabán’s showing in the Queens district attorney primary revealed that progressive supporters can rally national support and money for a local race.
lead_paragraph: Standing on the podium, surrounded by Democratic elected officials who had supported her first-ever candidacy, Tiffany Cabán gave a primary night victory speech on Tuesday that seemed unlikely a few months ago, and outright impossible a few years back.

headline_main: Why Tiffany Cabán May Be More Significant to Progressives Than Ocasio-Cortez
headline_print_headline: Cabán’s Primary Performance May Signal a ‘Huge Movement’ Is Roused
byline_original: By Jeffery C. Mays and Jan Ransom

abstract: Julián Castro excelled, Elizabeth Warren went from big factor at first to non-factor at times, and Cory Booker and Beto O’Rourke spoke the most but didn’t create singularly memorable moments.
snippet: Julián Castro excelled, Elizabeth Warren went from big factor at first to non-factor at times, and Cory Booker and Beto O’Rourke spoke the most but didn’t create singularly memorable moments.
lead_paragraph: Night One of the first Democratic debate of the 2020 race is in the books. There was no standout moment for any of the 10 candidates; no one suffered real damage either. While the NBC moderators tried to get the moderate and liberal Democrats to criticize each other, they were polite for the most part and stuck to their preferred issues and messages.

abstract: Elizabeth Warren, Bernie Sanders, Kamala Harris and other candidates finally take notice.
snippet: Elizabeth Warren, Bernie Sanders, Kamala Harris and other candidates finally take notice.
lead_paragraph: Child care is not something nice to have. It is a pressing crisis holding back the entire economy. Growth depends on more people working and working more productively. When parents who want to work can’t fully participate, America hurts only itself. Fortunately, many of the people running for president appear to have gotten the memo, making child care likely to be a topic during the Democratic debates.

abstract: The Senate health committee approved a suite of bills to address rising health costs — including surprise medical bills and prescription drug prices — and raise the legal smoking age.
snippet: The Senate health committee approved a suite of bills to address rising health costs — including surprise medical bills and prescription drug prices — and raise the legal smoking age.
lead_paragraph: WASHINGTON — The Senate health committee approved a package of bills on Wednesday aimed at lowering the cost of medical care, from ending surprise medical bills to curbing prescription drug price surges, with a rare bipartisan vote that could vault it toward final passage.
